article.linkText: Mystics need late rally to keep Mercury winless on the road
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Stacey Dales-Schuman scored 16 points and
sparked a late rally that helped the Washington Mystics to a 68-54
victory over the Phoenix Mercury on Tuesday night.

<photo1>

	   The Mystics (14-5) tied a franchise record for victories, set two
seasons ago when they made their lone playoff appearance.

	   Washington is unbeaten in eight home games this season, while
Phoenix (7-10) is winless in eight road games and has lost six
consecutive overall.

	   ''I'm grateful that this team has worked so hard,'' Washington
coach Marianne Stanley said. ''I'm really pleased that we're out in
front of the pack and others chase us.''

	   The Mystics, playing without injured All-Star forward Chamique
Holdsclaw for the fifth consecutive game and point guard Annie Burgess
for the second, took a 27-10 lead and seemed in control.

	   ''We've had a tough road stretch, and we're glad to be back
home,'' Dales-Schuman said. ''We've been away, and we felt we came
out with some energy tonight.''

	   Holdsclaw announced after the game that she is skipping the WNBA
All-Star Game, which will be next Monday in Washington.

	   Jennifer Gillom led Phoenix back, scoring 18 of her 26 points in
the second half as the Mercury took a 45-44 lead with just less than 10
minutes to play.

	   But Helen Luz and Dales-Schuman combined for three consecutive 3-pointers to give Washington the lead for good, 53-45 with 6:14
left.

   Luz broke out of a recent slump to hit the first one and
finished with 13 points, all but one on 3-pointers. Dales-Schuman
then hit consecutive 3s as the Mystics completed their 10-point
run.

	   Vicky Bullett added 10 points for the Mystics, who also got five
points and 12 rebounds from Murriel Page.
